public class JsDocument
extends DOM2Core.Document.Prototype
implements EventTarget, DocumentRange

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.Document class.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

addEventListener

public final void addEventListener(java.lang.String type,
                                   JsFunction<?> listener,
                                   java.lang.Boolean useCapture)

Adds an event handler function to the set of event handlers for this document. This is a DOM-standard method supported by all modern browsers except IE.

This method adds the specified event listener function to the set of listeners registered on this node to handle events of the specified type. If useCapture is true, the listener is registered as a capturing event listener. If useCapture is false, it is registered as a normal event listener.

This method may be called multiple times to register multiple event handlers for the same type of event on the same node. Note, however, that the DOM Specification makes no guarantees about the order in which multiple event handlers are invoked.

If the same event listener function is registered twice on the same node with the same type and useCapture arguments, the second registration is simply ignored. If a new event listener is registered on this node while an event is being handled at this node, the new event listener is not invoked for that event.

When a node is duplicated with JsNode.cloneNode(Boolean) or importNode(JsNode, Boolean), the event listeners registered for the original node are not copied.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
addEventListener in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be invoked.
listener - The event listener function that is invoked when an event of the specified type is dispatched to this node. When invoked, the listener function is passed an JsEvent object and is invoked as a method of the node on which it is registered.
useCapture - If true, the specified listener is to be invoked only during the capturing phase of event propagation. The more common value of false means that the listener is not invoked during the capturing phase but instead is invoked when this node is the actual event target or when the event bubbles up to this node from its original target.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
attachEvent(String, JsFunction), removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsElement.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsWindow.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

removeEventListener

public final void removeEventListener(java.lang.String type,
                                      JsFunction<?> listener,
                                      java.lang.Boolean useCapture)

Removes an event handler function from the set of handlers for this document. This is a standard DOM method implemented by all modern browsers except IE.

This method removes the specified event listener function. The type and useCapture arguments must be the same as they are in the corresponding call to addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean). If no event listener is found that matches the specified arguments, this method does nothing.

Once an event listener function has been removed by this method, it will no longer be invoked for the specified type of event on this node. This is true even if the event listener is removed by another event listener registered for the same type of event on the same node.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
removeEventListener in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be deleted.
listener - The event listener function that is to be removed.
useCapture - true if a capturing event listener is to be removed; false if a normal event listener is to be removed.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
detachEvent(String, JsFunction), addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsElement.removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsWindow.removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean)

attachEvent

public final void attachEvent(java.lang.String type,
                              JsFunction<?> listener)

Adds an event handler function to the set of handlers for this document. This is the IE-specific alternative to addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean).

This method is an IE-specific event registration method. It serves the same purpose as the standard addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean) method, which IE does not support, but is different from that function in several important ways:

  • Since the IE event model does not support event capturing, this method and detachEvent(String, JsFunction) expect only two arguments: the event type and the handler function.
  • The event handler names passed to the IE methods should include the "on" prefix.
  • Functions registered with this method are invoked with no JsEvent JsWindow.event property of JsWindow.window object.
  • Functions registered with this method are invoked as global functions, rather than as methods of the node on which the event occurred. That is, when an event handler registered with this method executes, the this keyword refers to JsWindow.window object, not to the event's target node.
  • This method allows the same event handler function to be registered more than once. When an event of the specified type occurs, the registered function is invoked as many times as it is registered.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsElement and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
attachEvent in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be invoked, with a leading "on" prefix.
listener - The event listener function that is invoked when an event of the specified type is dispatched to this node. This function is not passed any JsWindow.event property of the JsWindow object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), detachEvent(String, JsFunction), JsElement.attachEvent(String, JsFunction), JsWindow.attachEvent(String, JsFunction)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

dispatchEvent

public final java.lang.Boolean dispatchEvent(JsEvent evt)

Dispatches a synthetic event to this document.

This method dispatches a synthetic event created with createEvent(String) and initialized with the initialization method defined by the JsEvent or one of its subclasses. The node on which this method is called becomes the target of the event, but the event first propagates down the document tree during the capturing phase, and then, if the JsEvent.bubbles property of the event is true, it bubbles up the document tree after being handled at the event target itself.

Parameters:
evt - The JsEvent object to be dispatched.
Returns:
false if the JsEvent.preventDefault() method of evt is called at any time during the propagation of the event, or true otherwise.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsError object if evt is not initialized, or if its JsEvent.type property is null or the empty string. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
createEvent(String), JsEvent.initEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean), JsMouseEvent.initMouseEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean, JsWindow, Number, Number, Number, Number, Number, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Number, JsElement), JsElement.dispatchEvent(JsEvent)
JavaScript:

getElementById

public final JsElement getElementById(java.lang.String elementId)

Returns a descendant JsElement element of this document that has the specified value for its id attribute, or null if no such element exists in the document.

This method searches the document for an JsElement node with an id attribute whose value is elementId and returns that element. If no such element is found, it returns null. The value of the id attribute is intended to be unique within a document, and if this method finds more than one element with the specified elementId, it may return one at random, or it may return null.

This is an important and commonly used method because it provides a simple way to obtain the JsElement object that represents a specific document element.

For HTML documents, this method searches for an element based on the value of its id attribute. Use JsHTMLDocument.getElementsByName(String) to search for HTML elements based on the value of their name attributes.

For XML documents, this method performs its search using any attribute whose type is id, regardless of what the name of that attribute is. If, for example, because the XML parser ignored or could not locate the document's DTD, XML attribute types are not known, this method always returns null. In JavaScript, this method is not usually useful with XML documents. In fact, it was originally defined as a member of the HTMLDocument interface but was then moved to the Document interface in DOM Level 2.

Parameters:
elementId - The value of the id attribute of the desired element.
Returns:
The JsElement node that represents the document element with the specified id attribute or null if no such element is found.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
getElementsByTagName(String), getElementById(StringLike), JsHTMLDocument.getElementsByName(String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

getElementsByTagName

public final JsNodeList<? extends JsElement> getElementsByTagName(java.lang.String name)

Returns an array, technically a JsNodeList object, of all JsElement nodes in this document that have the specified tag name by traversing the entire document. The JsElement nodes appear in the returned array in the same order in which they appear in the document source.

Note that the JsElement.getElementsByTagName(String) method works just like this one but that traverses just the descendants of a single element, rather than the entire document. Do not confuse this method with JsHTMLDocument.getElementsByName(String), which searches for elements based on the value of their name attributes rather than by their tag names.

Parameters:
name - The tag name of the desired elements, or the value "*" to specify that all descendant elements should be returned, regardless of their tag names.
Returns:
An read-only array, technically a JsNodeList object, of all JsElement nodes in this document that have the specified tag name.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
getElementsByTagName(StringLike), getElementById(String), JsElement.getElementsByTagName(String), JsHTMLDocument.getElementsByName(String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

getElementsByTagNameNS

public final JsNodeList<? extends JsElement> getElementsByTagNameNS(java.lang.String namespaceURI,
                                                                    java.lang.String localName)

Returns an array of all JsElement nodes that have the specified tag name and name-space.

This method works like getElementsByTagName(String), except that the tag name of the desired elements is specified as a combination of a name space URI and a local name defined within that name space. This method is useful only with XML documents that use name spaces.

createEvent

public final JsEvent createEvent(java.lang.String eventType)

Creates a new synthetic JsEvent object of the named type.

In DOM Specification, this method is actually defined not by the DOM Document interface but by the DocumentEvent interface. If an implementation supports the Events module, the Document object always implements the DocumentEvent interface and supports this method. Note that Internet Explorer does not support the DOM Events module.

Parameters:
eventType - The name of the event module for which an JsEvent object is desired. Note that the value of this argument should not be the (singular) name of the DOM event interface to be created but instead should be the (plural) name of the DOM module that defines that interface. Valid event types are listed as follows:
  • HTMLEvents: creating a JsEvent object that must be initialized with the initialization method JsEvent.initEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean).
  • MouseEvents: creating a JsMouseEvent object that must be initialized with the initialization method JsMouseEvent.initMouseEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean, JsWindow, Number, Number, Number, Number, Number, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Number, JsElement).
  • UIEvents: creating a JsUIEvent object that must be initialized with the initialization method JsUIEvent.initUIEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean, JsWindow, Long).
Returns:
A newly created JsEvent object of the specified type.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.NOT_SUPPORTED_ERR if the implementation does not support events of the requested type. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
createEvent(StringLike)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

evaluate

public final JsXPathResult evaluate(java.lang.String xpathText,
                                    JsNode contextNode,
                                    JsFunction<? extends java.lang.String> namespaceURLMapper,
                                    java.lang.Number resultType,
                                    JsXPathResult result)

Evaluates an XPath query against this document.

This method evaluates the specified XPath expression against the given context node and returns an JsXPathResult object, using resultType to determine what the result type should be. If you want to evaluate an expression more than once, use createExpression(String) to compile the expression to a JsXPathExpression object and then use the JsXPathExpression.evaluate(JsNode, Number, JsXPathResult) method of that object.

See JsNode.selectNodes(String) and JsNode.selectSingleNode(String) for an IE-specific alternative.

Parameters:
xpathText - The string representing the XPath expression to evaluate.
contextNode - The node in this document against which the expression is to be evaluated.
namespaceURLMapper - A function that will map from a name space prefix to a full name space URL or null if no such mapping is required.
resultType - The type of object expected as a result, using XPath conversions to coerce the result. Possible values for the type are the constants defined by JsClient.XPathResult object.
result - A JsXPathResult object to be reused or null if you want a new JsXPathResult object to be created.
Returns:
A JsXPathResult object representing the evaluation of the expression against the given context node.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsError object if the xpathText contains a syntax error, if the result of the expression cannot be converted to the desired resultType, if the expression contains a name space prefix that cannot be resolved by namespaceURLMapper, or if contextNode is of the wrong type or is not associated with this document. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
createExpression(String, JsFunction), JsNode.selectNodes(String), JsNode.selectSingleNode(String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

importNode

public final JsNode importNode(JsNode importedNode,
                               java.lang.Boolean deep)

Makes a copy of a node from some other document that is suitable for insertion into this document.

This method is passed a node defined in another document and returns a copy of the node that is suitable for insertion into this document. If deep is true, all descendants of the node are also copied. The original node and its descendants are not modified in any way. The returned copy has its JsNode.ownerDocument property set to this document but has a JsNode.parentNode of null because it has not yet been inserted into the document. Event listener functions registered on the original node or tree are not copied.

When an JsElement node is imported, only the attributes that are explicitly specified in the source document are imported with it. When an JsAttr node is imported, its JsAttr.specified property is automatically set to true.

Parameters:
importedNode - The node to be imported.
deep - If true, recursively copy all descendants of importedNode as well.
Returns:
A copy of importedNode, and possibly all of its descendants if deep is true, with its JsNode.ownerDocument set to this document.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.NOT_SUPPORTED_ERR if importedNode is a JsDocument or JsDocumentType node, because those types of nodes cannot be imported. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsNode.cloneNode(Boolean)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

loadXML

public final void loadXML(java.lang.String text)

Parses a string of XML mark-up and stores the result in this document object.

This IE-specific method parses the specified string of XML text and builds a tree of DOM nodes in the current JsDocument object, discarding any nodes that previously existed in the JsDocument object.

This method does not exist on JsDocument objects that represent HTML documents. Before calling the method, you typically create a new, empty JsDocument object to hold the parsed content: 

 JsDocument doc = new JsDocument(Js.activeX("MSXML2.DOMDocument"));
 doc.loadXML(markup);

See JsDOMParser.parseFromString(String, String) for a non-IE alternative.

Parameters:
text - The XML mark-up to parse.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
loadXML(StringLike), JsDOMParser.parseFromString(String, String)
JavaScript:
